<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="THREDDS_Configuration"><span class="mw-headline-number">3</span> <a href="../index.php/Hyrax_-_THREDDS_Configuration" title="Hyrax - THREDDS Configuration">THREDDS Configuration</a></span></h2>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Logging_configuration"><span class="mw-headline-number">4</span> <a href="../index.php/Hyrax_-_Logging_Configuration" title="Hyrax - Logging Configuration">Logging configuration</a></span></h2>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Robots"><span class="mw-headline-number">5</span> Robots</span></h2>
<p>To correctly deploy a robots.txt file for Hyrax, you must correctly deploy it for Tomcat. This means that your robots.txt file must be accessible here:
</p>
<pre>   <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://you.host:port/robots.txt">http://you.host:port/robots.txt</a>
</pre>
<p>For example:
</p>
<pre>   <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.opendap.org/robots.txt">http://www.opendap.org/robots.txt</a>
</pre>
<p>Placing it lower in the URL path doesn't seem to work. 
</p><p>In order to get Tomcat to serve the file from that location you must place it in <b>$CATALINA_HOME/webapps/ROOT</b>
</p><p>If you still find that you system is being cruelly burdened with robot traffic then you might want to try the <a href="../index.php/Hyrax_-_OLFS_Configuration#BotBlocker_.28optional.29" title="Hyrax - OLFS Configuration">BotBlocker handler for the OLFS</a>.
</p>



